## White Gold vs. Platinum for a Pear Diamond Ring

This is the most important comparison for white gold pear buyers. Platinum and white gold are visually identical at arm's length when white gold's rhodium plating is fresh. The differences are real but often misunderstood.

| Factor | 14k White Gold | Platinum |
|--------|---------------|---------|
| Upfront cost | Lower — 30–40% cheaper for same setting | Higher |
| Long-term maintenance | Rhodium replating every 1–3 years (~$50–$200) | None — naturally white, never replates |
| Durability | Hard alloy mix — prong holds well | Extremely durable — metal flows rather than chips |
| V-prong for pear tip | Good in 14k; prong holds shape | Best overall — platinum's density protects the tip |
| Natural color | Yellow gold with rhodium surface | Naturally silver-white |
| Weight on finger | Lighter | Heavier — noticeably denser |
| Best for diamond color | D–G | D–G (identical requirement) |
| Long-term appearance | Replating keeps it bright; slightly different patina over time | Develops a natural "platinum grey" patina buyers often love |

**The ruling for white gold pear rings:** 14k white gold is the correct choice if you are budget-constrained and will maintain rhodium plating regularly. Platinum is the correct choice if you want zero maintenance, maximum V-prong security for the pear tip, or you prefer the natural platinum grey patina that develops over decades. The color grade decision is identical in both metals — D–G is required for either.

---

## 14k vs. 18k White Gold for a Pear Diamond Ring

**14k white gold (58.3% gold):** The higher alloy mix of 14k creates a harder metal than 18k. For pear diamond rings, this matters specifically at the V-prong — 14k's harder composition holds the tip prong more securely over 20+ years of daily wear. 14k is also 15–25% cheaper than 18k for the same setting and requires less frequent rhodium replating because the harder surface retains the coating longer.

**18k white gold (75% gold):** Higher gold content means 18k is marginally softer than 14k, with slightly lower rhodium retention, and costs more. The visual difference between 14k and 18k white gold is imperceptible — both look identical when rhodium-plated.

**The ruling:** 14k is the correct choice for pear diamond rings in white gold. The V-prong security advantage matters, the price saving is real, and there is no visual payoff for 18k in white gold the way there is in yellow or rose gold.

