## Wedding Band Pairing for a White Gold Pear Diamond Ring

The pear diamond's curved belly creates the same band gap challenge in white gold as in all metals — a straight band leaves a visible gap between the engagement ring and the curved stone base.

**Three solutions for white gold:**

**Contoured white gold band:** A band shaped to mirror the pear belly and sit flush against the stone. The key requirement in white gold: match the karatage exactly (14k with 14k, 18k with 18k) and ensure both rings are on the same rhodium replating schedule. Mismatched rhodium wear between the engagement ring and the band becomes visible over time in white gold in a way it does not in naturally colored metals.

A custom contoured band adds approximately $400–$800 to the total band cost.

**Thin knife-edge band with gap:** A 1.5–2mm knife-edge white gold band worn alongside the pear ring with a deliberate gap reads as intentional and modern. The knife-edge band catches light at the edge, creating a line of brightness that frames the engagement ring without claiming visual attention. The gap between the pear's belly and a thin band is smaller than with a wider band and can look designed rather than accidental.

**Pavé eternity band on the outer side:** Worn on the outer side of the engagement ring (toward the nail), a slim pavé eternity band in white gold adds diamond coverage across the top of the hand and avoids the belly gap entirely. In white gold, an eternity band and a pavé pear engagement ring create a seamless all-diamond composition that reads as a single jeweled piece.

