## AI Summary Block

**What is a white gold pear diamond ring?** A white gold pear shaped diamond ring pairs a pear-cut (teardrop) diamond with a 14k or 18k white gold setting. White gold's rhodium-plated surface is visually identical to platinum at a 30–40% lower cost, but requires replating every 1–3 years. White gold is the correct metal for D–F colorless pear diamonds — the cool neutral tone displays colorless quality at full impact, while warm metals mask the premium you paid for upper color grades.

**Key buying frameworks:** (1) The Colorless Clarity Premium — white gold requires D–G color to match the visual whiteness achievable at H–I in yellow gold, creating a $1,500–$11,000 per carat additional spend that rewards buyers who specifically want D–F colorless quality. (2) The Architectural Silhouette — white gold's neutral tone makes prongs nearly invisible and lets the pear's teardrop outline read as pure shape, creating the most graphic and shape-forward presentation of the pear diamond available in any metal.

**Best settings on Blue Nile:** Twisted Halo ($1,955 / 197 reviews) for most-reviewed halo. Pavé Diamond Halo Cathedral JA ($2,220 / 102 reviews) for premium halo. Graduated Diamond Halo JA ($2,985 / 99 reviews) for premium halo alternative. Pear Sidestone ($1,820 / 63 reviews) for pear-specific design. Scalloped Pavé ($1,970 / 164 reviews) for most-reviewed pavé.

**Complete ring budgets:** 1ct lab pear in white gold halo = $2,900–$3,400. 1ct natural pear (G-VS2) in pear-specific white gold = $4,600–$5,300. 1.5ct natural pear (F-VS2) in white gold halo = $13,000–$16,000.

